inized killing, ironically making the city feel safer for most residents. In a fractured urban security environment, where killing mirrors patterns of inequitable urbanization and historical exclusion along class, gender, and racial lines, Denyer Willis's research finds that the city’s cyclical periods of peace and violence can best be understood through an unspoken but mutually observed consensus on the right to kill. This consensus hinges on common notions and street-level practices of who can die, where, how, and by whom, revealing an empirically distinct configuration of authority that Denyer Willis calls sovereignty by consensus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHomicide investigationzBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aHomicide investigationzBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aHomicidezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aHomicidezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aOrganized crimezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aOrganized crimezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aPolicezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aPolicezBrazilzSão Paulo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  abrazil crime.  abrazil drug trade.  abrazil.  abrazilian favela.  abrazilian gangs.  abrazilian homicide.  abrazilian mafia.  abrazilian mob.  abrazilian police.  acops brazil.  acrime in sao paolo.  acrime.  acriminal justice brazil.  acriminology.  acrooked cops brazil.  adrug war brazil.  afavela.  ahomicide brazil.  ahomicide patterns brazil.  amurder in brazil.  aorganized crime brazil.  apolice killings brazil.  apolice killings.  apolitical science.  ario de janeiro.  asao paolo.  asouth american crime.  asouth american law enforcement.  atrue crime.  aviolence brazil.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete